1
00:00:04,776 --> 00:00:06,478
<i>I compared the procurement list Tsuda had</i>

2
00:00:06,544 --> 00:00:09,180
with the subsidiary ledger
from the Karashima Metal Factory.

3
00:00:09,247 --> 00:00:12,350
In Tsuda's procurement list,
there was SNCM.

4
00:00:12,417 --> 00:00:14,219
This metal is used for…

5
00:00:14,786 --> 00:00:15,653
handguns.

6
00:00:15,720 --> 00:00:18,123
<i>That gun might not</i>
<i>have been meant for use,</i>

7
00:00:18,189 --> 00:00:20,024
<i>but rather something</i>
<i>manufactured at the factory.</i>

8
00:00:20,091 --> 00:00:23,461
<i>Tsuda was probably investigating</i>
<i>the gun smugglers.</i>

9
00:00:23,528 --> 00:00:25,830
<i>If some kind of incident happened then…</i>

10
00:00:25,897 --> 00:00:28,066
The ones who killed our parents

11
00:00:28,633 --> 00:00:30,268
might be the Igarashi-gumi.

12
00:00:45,283 --> 00:00:46,317
He's a weirdo.

13
00:00:46,384 --> 00:00:47,252
Let's go.

14
00:01:16,281 --> 00:01:18,283
-I’ll leave the rest to you.
-Yes.

15
00:01:25,690 --> 00:01:27,492
How did you know he was a thief?

16
00:01:28,526 --> 00:01:29,527
Just a coincidence.

17
00:01:30,295 --> 00:01:33,665
You happened to be looking at him,
and he happened to commit the crime?

18
00:01:34,732 --> 00:01:35,767
What is it?

19
00:01:36,901 --> 00:01:39,704
If you got serious,
you might just be a decent detective.

20
00:01:40,605 --> 00:01:43,541
If I had lived properly,
I wouldn't even be a detective.

21
00:01:48,313 --> 00:01:49,948
Then what would you be doing?

22
00:01:50,582 --> 00:01:53,017
Who knows?
I've never even thought about it.

23
00:01:53,084 --> 00:01:55,486
You would probably
be getting a divorce by now.

24
00:01:55,553 --> 00:01:57,922
At least let me get married first.

25
00:01:59,157 --> 00:02:02,193
Haruko investigated Tsuda’s room
the other day, right?

26
00:02:03,861 --> 00:02:05,029
Three…

27
00:02:19,544 --> 00:02:21,279
This is terrible.

28
00:02:32,023 --> 00:02:34,292
Haruko already checked this place?

29
00:02:34,959 --> 00:02:36,127
Should we lift the futon?

30
00:02:36,194 --> 00:02:39,464
Anyway, what was the motive
of the guys who attacked him?

31
00:02:42,066 --> 00:02:42,767
Hey.

32
00:02:43,901 --> 00:02:44,836
Oh, hey.

33
00:02:44,902 --> 00:02:46,404
Wrong room.

34
00:02:47,772 --> 00:02:51,276
The ones who trashed Tsuda’s room
were members of the Igarashi-gumi.

35
00:02:51,342 --> 00:02:52,844
The Igarashi-gumi?

36
00:02:53,645 --> 00:02:57,081
The guy who stole Tsuda’s backpack
told me after I bought him a beer.

37
00:02:57,148 --> 00:02:58,516
Hey, where is it?

38
00:02:58,583 --> 00:02:59,884
Hold it right there!

39
00:02:59,951 --> 00:03:01,219
Hey, Tsuda, you bastard!

40
00:03:01,286 --> 00:03:02,820
Come back!

41
00:03:02,887 --> 00:03:03,921
Hey!

42
00:03:07,859 --> 00:03:11,596
The heck? There's nothing here,
just books…

43
00:03:13,398 --> 00:03:16,167
<i>On the back of the Karashima</i>
<i>Metal Factory photo,</i>

44
00:03:16,234 --> 00:03:18,002
<i>it said "tools."</i>

45
00:03:19,003 --> 00:03:21,939
<i>It seems those guys took</i>
<i>all the notebooks and files.</i>

46
00:03:22,640 --> 00:03:24,876
"Tools" is slang for handguns.

47
00:03:25,443 --> 00:03:28,479
No doubt, that factory
is connected to the Igarashi-gumi.

48
00:03:29,213 --> 00:03:32,583
Then what they took
was Tsuda’s research notebook.

49
00:03:32,650 --> 00:03:34,018
That notebook

50
00:03:35,086 --> 00:03:37,622
might contain clues from 30 years ago.

51
00:03:39,090 --> 00:03:42,794
Problem now is… how do we
get close to the Igarashi-gumi?

52
00:03:44,429 --> 00:03:46,264
CHINESE RESTAURANT
MOCCHAN

53
00:03:49,500 --> 00:03:51,169
Welcome. Oh, hey.

54
00:03:51,235 --> 00:03:52,136
Well…

55
00:03:52,203 --> 00:03:53,504
Hello.

56
00:03:53,571 --> 00:03:55,707
-Oh, hello.
-Please check this.

57
00:03:55,773 --> 00:03:57,342
We have to hurry.

58
00:03:57,408 --> 00:04:00,745
We need to get that notebook
before the gang members dispose of it.

59
00:04:01,612 --> 00:04:03,281
What happened back then?

60
00:04:04,082 --> 00:04:06,617
If we find out what went on
at the factory, I'm sure…

61
00:04:07,518 --> 00:04:09,153
Sure of what?

62
00:04:13,424 --> 00:04:16,260
What are you two
investigating about the factory?

63
00:04:16,828 --> 00:04:18,096
Fumi.

64
00:04:20,031 --> 00:04:21,065
Makoto,

65
00:04:21,733 --> 00:04:22,767
it's nice to see you.

66
00:04:24,936 --> 00:04:26,504
Minoru.

67
00:04:26,571 --> 00:04:29,073
I heard you're with
the Kanagawa Prefectural Police?

68
00:04:29,140 --> 00:04:30,308
What?

69
00:04:31,175 --> 00:04:33,378
It seems you visited our tax accountant

70
00:04:34,345 --> 00:04:36,314
and looked at the factory ledger.

71
00:04:38,416 --> 00:04:41,786
Sneaking around isn't a good thing.

72
00:04:42,787 --> 00:04:43,821
I'm sorry.

73
00:04:43,888 --> 00:04:46,157
I just wanted to know
about the metal used for the robot.

74
00:04:46,224 --> 00:04:47,592
Is that really all?

75
00:04:49,026 --> 00:04:50,762
Yes, just that.

76
00:04:51,996 --> 00:04:52,864
What about you?

77
00:04:54,699 --> 00:04:55,733
Me?

78
00:04:56,367 --> 00:04:58,569
Is there anything you’re hiding from us?

79
00:05:03,808 --> 00:05:04,709
What do you think?

80
00:05:04,776 --> 00:05:06,611
I’m the one asking.

81
00:05:08,646 --> 00:05:10,415
-What happened at that factory…
-Mogi!

82
00:05:11,015 --> 00:05:12,950
-Thanks for the meal.
-Oh, sure.

83
00:05:13,017 --> 00:05:13,851
Fumi!

84
00:05:16,487 --> 00:05:18,289
I'm glad I saw you.

85
00:05:19,424 --> 00:05:20,625
Mogi.

86
00:05:20,691 --> 00:05:22,226
You can keep the change.

87
00:05:23,127 --> 00:05:24,595
You're too kind.

88
00:05:24,662 --> 00:05:26,030
Thank you very much.

89
00:05:35,106 --> 00:05:36,741
Was this really for the best?

90
00:05:37,408 --> 00:05:38,342
Mr. Uno.

91
00:05:38,409 --> 00:05:39,277
THE EMPTY GARDEN

92
00:05:39,343 --> 00:05:41,045
Please remember…

93
00:05:42,413 --> 00:05:43,981
what happened that day.

94
00:05:46,784 --> 00:05:48,052
Doctor.

95
00:05:50,254 --> 00:05:51,923
Now, you're quits.

96
00:05:52,824 --> 00:05:54,091
You're even.

97
00:06:00,598 --> 00:06:02,667
Nice and even.

98
00:06:03,868 --> 00:06:05,236
Nice and even.

99
00:06:08,039 --> 00:06:08,940
Nice…

100
00:06:14,545 --> 00:06:18,015
The deceased is
Ayaka Nishiura, 29 years old.

101
00:06:18,082 --> 00:06:22,253
She was in a vehicle accident, brought
to the hospital, and pronounced dead.

102
00:06:22,753 --> 00:06:24,088
Examiner Tagusari.

103
00:06:24,956 --> 00:06:28,226
<i>As the victim's fingernails</i>
<i>were bright red, we performed an autopsy.</i>

104
00:06:28,292 --> 00:06:32,763
The results showed the cause of death
was not injuries from the collision,

105
00:06:32,830 --> 00:06:34,599
but carbon monoxide poisoning.

106
00:06:36,767 --> 00:06:38,269
What does that mean?

107
00:06:38,336 --> 00:06:39,904
Carbon monoxide…

108
00:06:39,971 --> 00:06:42,540
But the car wasn't on fire, right?

109
00:06:42,607 --> 00:06:45,710
We believe she inhaled it
before the accident, while driving.

110
00:06:46,611 --> 00:06:48,279
While driving?

111
00:06:49,046 --> 00:06:52,483
After the autopsy, the coroner requested
an investigation of the vehicle.

112
00:06:52,550 --> 00:06:53,818
As a result,

113
00:06:53,885 --> 00:06:56,454
it was found that the flange
connecting the muffler

114
00:06:56,521 --> 00:06:58,890
and the exhaust tailpipe
was unnaturally loose.

115
00:06:58,956 --> 00:06:59,824
The flange?

116
00:06:59,891 --> 00:07:01,459
This part right here.

117
00:07:01,526 --> 00:07:02,827
NISHIURA
FLANGE / ENGINE

118
00:07:02,894 --> 00:07:05,630
While the car was stopped
at a red light, exhaust gas entered

119
00:07:05,696 --> 00:07:07,465
through a crack in the car's lower part.

120
00:07:07,965 --> 00:07:09,033
That is all.

121
00:07:11,469 --> 00:07:13,905
Then she had carbon monoxide poisoning.

122
00:07:13,971 --> 00:07:15,339
In other words,

123
00:07:16,040 --> 00:07:17,375
it was murder?

124
00:07:27,418 --> 00:07:28,853
Thanks for your cooperation.

125
00:07:28,920 --> 00:07:30,521
-It’s on the fourth floor. Follow me.
-Yes.

126
00:07:31,622 --> 00:07:33,291
-Here you go.
-Thank you.

127
00:07:33,357 --> 00:07:34,859
Excuse me.

128
00:07:45,102 --> 00:07:47,371
This is Ayaka Nishiura’s residence, right?

129
00:07:49,407 --> 00:07:50,608
Yes.

130
00:07:50,675 --> 00:07:51,809
Who are you?

131
00:07:52,410 --> 00:07:54,545
I'm Kudo from the Aoi Station.

132
00:07:54,612 --> 00:07:57,548
Pardon me, but what was
your relationship with Ms. Nishiura?

133
00:07:58,115 --> 00:08:01,018
I was dating Ayaka. My name is Agatsuma.

134
00:08:03,354 --> 00:08:04,922
Why are the police here?

135
00:08:05,790 --> 00:08:07,959
There’s something
that caught our attention.

136
00:08:09,193 --> 00:08:11,162
Ayaka's death was an accident, wasn't it?

137
00:08:12,930 --> 00:08:15,967
Has she been acting strangely lately?

138
00:08:20,638 --> 00:08:21,872
She changed.

139
00:08:22,473 --> 00:08:24,775
Quite a lot compared to back then.

140
00:08:29,046 --> 00:08:30,448
Three years ago,

141
00:08:31,682 --> 00:08:35,753
Ayaka accidentally
killed someone in a car crash.

142
00:08:36,687 --> 00:08:38,889
It's so warm! Thank you!

143
00:08:47,798 --> 00:08:50,067
<i>Ayaka didn't commit any violation.</i>

144
00:08:51,702 --> 00:08:53,871
She was just driving normally.

145
00:08:56,907 --> 00:08:58,709
If that person hadn't jumped out,

146
00:08:59,810 --> 00:09:02,146
she never would have caused the accident.

147
00:09:03,948 --> 00:09:06,817
It was one week before our wedding.

148
00:09:09,153 --> 00:09:10,454
Though it was unintentional,

149
00:09:11,288 --> 00:09:14,325
she was depressed
about having killed someone.

150
00:09:15,192 --> 00:09:16,694
She couldn't work,

151
00:09:17,395 --> 00:09:19,697
get married, or do anything.

152
00:09:21,465 --> 00:09:26,170
But over time,
she was moving forward little by little.

153
00:09:31,542 --> 00:09:34,045
I had just proposed for the second time.

154
00:09:35,646 --> 00:09:36,814
I'm sorry.

155
00:09:46,357 --> 00:09:49,026
It’s just… unbearable, isn't it?

156
00:09:52,963 --> 00:09:55,032
A second proposal, huh?

157
00:09:57,134 --> 00:10:01,005
The dead do not get a second chance.

158
00:10:05,543 --> 00:10:09,413
Ayaka Nishiura, who died yesterday,
caused an accident three years ago

159
00:10:09,480 --> 00:10:11,782
that resulted in the death
of Ms. Yoko Uno.

160
00:10:11,849 --> 00:10:15,519
At the time, Ms. Nishiura was not found
negligent and not prosecuted.

161
00:10:16,153 --> 00:10:18,189
But it seems Yoko’s husband,

162
00:10:19,090 --> 00:10:20,391
Takamichi Uno,

163
00:10:20,458 --> 00:10:23,961
repeatedly protested to the police
and prosecutors about that result.

164
00:10:24,895 --> 00:10:26,731
Do you think the husband killed her?

165
00:10:27,565 --> 00:10:28,799
Did you find something?

166
00:10:29,300 --> 00:10:30,134
Hey.

167
00:10:30,201 --> 00:10:31,035
Yes.

168
00:10:32,203 --> 00:10:36,507
Early in the morning of the day
Ayaka Nishiura died, a person was seen

169
00:10:36,574 --> 00:10:39,777
crawling under her car
in the apartment's parking lot.

170
00:10:40,711 --> 00:10:42,513
Looks like Uno.

171
00:10:42,580 --> 00:10:46,417
Furthermore, Uno is a mechanic
at an automobile factory.

172
00:10:46,484 --> 00:10:48,953
That’s why he was able
to tamper with the flange.

173
00:10:49,019 --> 00:10:50,688
Guess this case is open-and-shut.

174
00:10:51,222 --> 00:10:54,759
I’ll question Uno tomorrow,
so I have to report to the superiors.

175
00:10:56,527 --> 00:10:59,196
But it was an unavoidable
accident, wasn't it?

176
00:10:59,263 --> 00:11:01,198
She suddenly jumped onto the road.

177
00:11:01,265 --> 00:11:04,268
It’s just something
that could happen to anyone.

178
00:11:05,169 --> 00:11:08,305
Uno did it as revenge
for his wife's death.

179
00:11:13,444 --> 00:11:15,780
Would you really seek revenge for that?

180
00:11:18,549 --> 00:11:20,518
And three years have passed already.

181
00:11:21,485 --> 00:11:23,487
Maybe he tried to forgive, but couldn't.

182
00:11:23,554 --> 00:11:26,390
For someone with a grudge,
his method was too roundabout.

183
00:11:27,024 --> 00:11:29,093
If you hate someone,
you would confront them.

184
00:11:29,827 --> 00:11:31,796
Are you saying Uno isn't the culprit?

185
00:11:35,666 --> 00:11:36,734
Who knows?

186
00:11:41,705 --> 00:11:45,810
He asked me about the shootings
in Yomogida Town 30 years ago.

187
00:11:45,876 --> 00:11:47,578
From 30 years ago?

188
00:11:47,645 --> 00:11:51,515
He said a colleague
at Totsuka North was pursuing it,

189
00:11:51,582 --> 00:11:55,152
but apparently, Totsuka North
isn't handling any such case.

190
00:11:55,719 --> 00:11:58,522
Do you know
what Tagusari is investigating?

191
00:12:22,213 --> 00:12:23,247
You're Ms. Fumi…

192
00:12:24,248 --> 00:12:25,783
Karashima, right?

193
00:12:27,084 --> 00:12:28,352
Who are you?

194
00:12:30,487 --> 00:12:31,622
This…

195
00:12:31,689 --> 00:12:33,090
Can you buy this off me?

196
00:12:34,391 --> 00:12:37,628
Everything about
what happened 30 years ago

197
00:12:38,162 --> 00:12:39,496
is written here.

198
00:12:45,936 --> 00:12:49,039
ASAI AUTOMOBILE INC.

199
00:12:53,410 --> 00:12:55,079
I'm from the Aoi Station.

200
00:12:55,746 --> 00:12:57,248
You're Takamichi Uno, correct?

201
00:12:59,483 --> 00:13:00,317
Yes.

202
00:13:00,951 --> 00:13:05,689
Where were you two days ago,
May 13th, around 4:00 a.m.?

203
00:13:07,224 --> 00:13:10,594
-I was sleeping at home.
-Is there anyone who can vouch for that?

204
00:13:11,729 --> 00:13:13,030
No one.

205
00:13:13,998 --> 00:13:16,467
My wife passed away,
and I don't have children.

206
00:13:17,968 --> 00:13:21,005
You know Ayaka Nishiura, don't you?

207
00:13:29,480 --> 00:13:30,581
Mr. Uno?

208
00:13:33,751 --> 00:13:35,419
There’s no way I could forget.

209
00:13:36,053 --> 00:13:37,755
What about Ms. Nishiura’s accident?

210
00:13:38,889 --> 00:13:40,124
I saw it on the news.

211
00:13:40,190 --> 00:13:42,893
Could you come to the station
to give a detailed account?

212
00:13:43,560 --> 00:13:45,029
I have plans today.

213
00:14:13,590 --> 00:14:15,125
The city office?

214
00:14:22,099 --> 00:14:23,167
Thank you so much.

215
00:14:23,233 --> 00:14:24,368
Yes, come back anytime.

216
00:14:24,435 --> 00:14:27,438
You might think you're not
doing great as a mom, but you are!

217
00:14:27,504 --> 00:14:29,373
So cheer up, okay?

218
00:14:33,544 --> 00:14:34,845
Bye-bye!

219
00:14:36,747 --> 00:14:38,382
Thank you for waiting.

220
00:14:38,449 --> 00:14:39,917
Shall we go inside?

221
00:14:46,757 --> 00:14:49,159
WELFARE OFFICE
CONSULTING ROOM

222
00:14:49,226 --> 00:14:50,761
It seems Mr. Uno has been using

223
00:14:50,828 --> 00:14:53,263
the consultation service here
for three years.

224
00:14:53,330 --> 00:14:55,099
So after the accident?

225
00:14:55,766 --> 00:14:58,869
He started coming for advice
after losing his wife.

226
00:15:02,639 --> 00:15:04,475
Seems that way.

227
00:15:08,278 --> 00:15:11,915
Just having someone listen to you
gives a sense of relief.

228
00:15:14,251 --> 00:15:17,421
Staff here visited my home too.

229
00:15:18,322 --> 00:15:20,090
My mother was so annoyed, though.

230
00:15:25,162 --> 00:15:26,663
What about your home?

231
00:15:29,033 --> 00:15:31,268
What kind of person is your mother?

232
00:15:39,410 --> 00:15:41,145
Couldn't hide anything from her.

233
00:15:43,580 --> 00:15:44,748
If I lied

234
00:15:45,616 --> 00:15:47,551
or hid something, she would find out.

235
00:15:49,653 --> 00:15:51,789
She might have bugged us.

236
00:15:56,960 --> 00:15:58,228
That’s nice.

237
00:15:59,129 --> 00:16:00,497
What’s nice about it?

238
00:16:02,933 --> 00:16:03,767
It just…

239
00:16:04,368 --> 00:16:06,537
feels like a real family.

240
00:16:14,545 --> 00:16:17,481
Please contact me
whenever you feel like it.

241
00:16:17,548 --> 00:16:18,816
Thank you very much.

242
00:16:20,017 --> 00:16:21,285
The subject is leaving.

243
00:16:24,154 --> 00:16:27,057
Sorry to bother you at work.
I'm Kudo from the Aoi Station.

244
00:16:27,124 --> 00:16:27,958
Oh, hello.

245
00:16:28,025 --> 00:16:28,859
I'm Tagusari.

246
00:16:30,794 --> 00:16:31,795
Mr. Tagusari?

247
00:16:34,932 --> 00:16:37,067
Oh, it's nothing. Oh, my.

248
00:16:37,134 --> 00:16:39,103
I just thought, it's such a rare name.

249
00:16:40,037 --> 00:16:40,871
Oh, right.

250
00:16:41,505 --> 00:16:43,807
I’m from the Welfare
and Health Department.

251
00:16:43,874 --> 00:16:45,209
The name is Hatano.

252
00:16:47,511 --> 00:16:48,479
Thank you.

253
00:16:48,545 --> 00:16:49,379
WELFARE CONSULTANT

254
00:16:49,446 --> 00:16:50,914
Please have a seat.

255
00:16:52,249 --> 00:16:53,917
I’ll make some tea now.

256
00:16:57,754 --> 00:17:00,691
We want to ask about Mr. Uno,
whom you are counseling.

257
00:17:00,757 --> 00:17:03,760
What kind of things
does he consult with you about?

258
00:17:07,264 --> 00:17:10,701
Have you ever heard
the name Ayaka Nishiura?

259
00:17:13,403 --> 00:17:15,038
I’m sorry, but…

260
00:17:15,672 --> 00:17:16,740
I cannot answer that.

261
00:17:19,176 --> 00:17:22,846
Our relationship with consultees
is built on trust.

262
00:17:23,580 --> 00:17:26,250
I can't disclose information
without their consent.

263
00:17:26,316 --> 00:17:28,952
There’s a possibility it’s related
to a criminal case.

264
00:17:29,019 --> 00:17:31,155
Please, you must understand.

265
00:17:33,924 --> 00:17:35,192
Here.

266
00:17:39,730 --> 00:17:41,431
Were you able to solve his problems?

267
00:17:44,368 --> 00:17:46,103
The reasons Mr. Uno came here.

268
00:17:49,573 --> 00:17:51,508
"What can talking even change?"

269
00:17:52,176 --> 00:17:53,310
Is that what you think?

270
00:18:03,620 --> 00:18:04,721
But…

271
00:18:04,788 --> 00:18:07,758
isn't it painful to keep it
all bottled up inside?

272
00:18:11,862 --> 00:18:13,764
"No one understands anyway."

273
00:18:15,666 --> 00:18:17,968
"That's why I don't trust anyone."

274
00:18:19,636 --> 00:18:23,740
If you keep listening
only to your own voice like that,

275
00:18:24,875 --> 00:18:29,780
eventually you lose sight
of what's at your core.

276
00:18:32,349 --> 00:18:34,718
You come to hate what you love,

277
00:18:35,552 --> 00:18:37,955
or pretend to be fine when you're scared…

278
00:18:40,857 --> 00:18:41,925
For example,

279
00:18:42,993 --> 00:18:44,428
even to those close to you.

280
00:18:47,998 --> 00:18:52,903
I'm here to help nurture
that core so it can bloom.

281
00:18:54,171 --> 00:18:57,107
I will cooperate with you,
but there are things I can't do.

282
00:18:59,443 --> 00:19:01,645
Didn't that give you the chills?

283
00:19:01,712 --> 00:19:04,314
It's like she saw right through us.

284
00:19:32,876 --> 00:19:34,745
<i>The one I'm stuck on is the mother.</i>

285
00:19:34,811 --> 00:19:35,812
TELESEEK
ONE NEW MESSAGE

286
00:19:35,879 --> 00:19:38,348
<i>I saw a TeleSeek notification</i>
<i>on her phone.</i>

287
00:19:38,415 --> 00:19:40,984
<i>That app that doesn't store</i>
<i>message history?</i>

288
00:19:49,459 --> 00:19:51,895
Thank you. It's a real help.

289
00:19:56,833 --> 00:20:00,904
MAKOTO TAGUSARI
LOOK INTO THIS WELFARE WORKER FOR ME

290
00:20:04,441 --> 00:20:08,045
-Why don't you get something to read?
-There’s nothing I want to read.

291
00:20:08,545 --> 00:20:11,515
Is that Igarashi-gumi guy really coming?

292
00:20:17,854 --> 00:20:18,722
Did you see?

293
00:20:19,923 --> 00:20:20,991
See what?

294
00:20:21,725 --> 00:20:23,293
So that’s your type.

295
00:20:24,661 --> 00:20:26,430
I wasn't even looking.

296
00:20:26,997 --> 00:20:28,865
How many years has it been?

297
00:20:29,366 --> 00:20:31,068
You should get a girlfriend soon.

298
00:20:31,134 --> 00:20:34,171
-Shut up, leave me alone.
-You liked her, didn't you?

299
00:20:34,237 --> 00:20:36,807
I've known you since you were this big.

300
00:20:40,977 --> 00:20:41,945
Haruko.

301
00:20:42,012 --> 00:20:42,846
Yes.

302
00:20:46,650 --> 00:20:47,918
0.7, right?

303
00:20:47,984 --> 00:20:48,919
Yes.

304
00:20:49,519 --> 00:20:53,256
-It's your first buy, so I put in extra.
-Thanks.

305
00:20:57,227 --> 00:20:59,963
Guess there's no point
in arresting a low-level grunt.

306
00:21:03,433 --> 00:21:05,202
But, the Igarashi-gumi

307
00:21:05,268 --> 00:21:08,939
making college students push drugs?
Times sure have changed.

308
00:21:09,005 --> 00:21:11,475
These days, they prefer disposable labor.

309
00:21:15,779 --> 00:21:19,716
However, that also makes
the loose ends easier to find.

310
00:21:25,756 --> 00:21:28,225
If you hate it that much,
why don't you quit?

311
00:21:29,793 --> 00:21:32,963
Quit selling stuff like that,
and just work a normal job.

312
00:21:36,099 --> 00:21:38,735
You’re still young, after all.

313
00:21:38,802 --> 00:21:40,737
Yoshiyuki Nakajima.

314
00:21:41,671 --> 00:21:43,073
How do you know my name?

315
00:21:43,940 --> 00:21:46,076
We already have your gang's information.

316
00:21:47,310 --> 00:21:48,879
You really want to quit, right?

317
00:21:50,614 --> 00:21:52,682
But if I quit, I'll get killed.

318
00:21:55,385 --> 00:21:57,187
Shall I help you escape?

319
00:21:58,321 --> 00:22:01,491
In exchange,
tell me the day the drugs are delivered

320
00:22:01,558 --> 00:22:04,194
to your Igarashi-gumi boss.

321
00:22:10,500 --> 00:22:12,269
What are you doing here?

322
00:22:15,205 --> 00:22:19,009
Fumi is at work, so I came in her stead.

323
00:22:20,177 --> 00:22:21,144
But…

324
00:22:21,211 --> 00:22:24,247
I just got a message
saying her work is done.

325
00:22:24,915 --> 00:22:26,016
I see.

326
00:22:26,082 --> 00:22:26,983
Yes.

327
00:22:28,685 --> 00:22:30,987
Oh, welcome back.

328
00:22:31,054 --> 00:22:31,922
You're home?

329
00:22:31,988 --> 00:22:34,324
Yes, I came back just now.

330
00:22:35,125 --> 00:22:37,928
Mogi, thanks!

331
00:22:37,994 --> 00:22:39,095
-It was nothing.
-Yes!

332
00:22:39,162 --> 00:22:41,398
Thanks to you, I got some great photos.

333
00:22:41,465 --> 00:22:42,732
I’m glad.

334
00:22:43,400 --> 00:22:46,303
I heard… it was an important job?

335
00:22:46,369 --> 00:22:48,672
Yes, an advertisement.

336
00:22:48,738 --> 00:22:50,807
It's a huge job.

337
00:22:50,874 --> 00:22:52,342
Yukiteru?

338
00:22:53,510 --> 00:22:57,314
Since I'm here,
I thought I would go home with you, Mom.

339
00:22:57,380 --> 00:22:59,983
Karu, that's enough for today.

340
00:23:00,050 --> 00:23:02,652
I'll quickly clean the bathtub.

341
00:23:03,753 --> 00:23:05,322
The coffee is ready.

342
00:23:05,388 --> 00:23:06,790
Thank you.

343
00:23:08,592 --> 00:23:12,062
Mogi. Stay and have some coffee
until Karu is done.

344
00:23:12,562 --> 00:23:14,297
-Okay?
-Thank you.

345
00:23:15,966 --> 00:23:17,133
Mogi.

346
00:23:17,834 --> 00:23:19,202
Did you hear anything?

347
00:23:20,103 --> 00:23:23,006
No, I didn't talk to the doctor…

348
00:23:23,073 --> 00:23:25,675
Not that, I meant those brothers.

349
00:23:27,878 --> 00:23:29,579
Makoto and Minoru?

350
00:23:30,380 --> 00:23:34,251
Is the notebook they were talking
about the one that Tsuda had?

351
00:23:35,585 --> 00:23:38,355
No, I don't know anything.

352
00:23:38,421 --> 00:23:40,023
How troublesome.

353
00:23:41,057 --> 00:23:44,194
If strange rumors start,
it will affect my work.

354
00:24:02,579 --> 00:24:03,813
Oh, right.

355
00:24:04,948 --> 00:24:06,283
Take this with you.

356
00:24:07,217 --> 00:24:09,352
Karu likes sweets, doesn't she?

357
00:24:10,153 --> 00:24:10,987
Here.

358
00:24:16,693 --> 00:24:17,527
Are you okay?

359
00:24:18,061 --> 00:24:18,962
All right?

360
00:24:25,368 --> 00:24:26,336
What's wrong?

361
00:24:28,505 --> 00:24:30,440
It's nothing.

362
00:24:31,174 --> 00:24:32,976
You got a class reunion invite.

363
00:24:35,078 --> 00:24:36,379
Throw it away.

364
00:24:36,880 --> 00:24:37,747
Are you sure?

365
00:24:38,348 --> 00:24:39,783
I have nothing to say to them.

366
00:24:46,289 --> 00:24:49,726
It's all complaints about wives
and worries about raising kids.

367
00:24:49,793 --> 00:24:51,227
Those are the only topics.

368
00:24:52,062 --> 00:24:55,699
And once they get drunk,
someone will start talking about that day.

369
00:24:57,167 --> 00:24:59,002
"Tagusari worked hard."

370
00:24:59,836 --> 00:25:02,272
"Tagusari did well getting past it."

371
00:25:04,107 --> 00:25:05,842
"We're friends for life."

372
00:25:07,310 --> 00:25:10,180
Even though they forgot all about
what happened until they saw us.

373
00:25:10,747 --> 00:25:13,583
I can't stand being the subject
of gossip for their drinking sessions.

374
00:25:16,353 --> 00:25:17,487
Compared to that…

375
00:25:18,955 --> 00:25:21,191
it’s much better to drink alone.

376
00:25:27,764 --> 00:25:29,799
I'm hungry. Is there anything to eat?

377
00:25:30,600 --> 00:25:33,703
-I can make some <i>chukadon</i>.
-Extra quail eggs, please.

378
00:25:33,770 --> 00:25:34,804
Got it.

379
00:25:42,412 --> 00:25:44,981
When will you catch them?

380
00:25:45,048 --> 00:25:48,018
Why did my mom and dad die?

381
00:25:49,452 --> 00:25:52,389
<i>Isn't it painful to keep it</i>
<i>all bottled up inside?</i>

382
00:25:58,795 --> 00:25:59,763
What's wrong?

383
00:26:00,263 --> 00:26:02,332
I can't break Uno's alibi.

384
00:26:02,932 --> 00:26:06,002
The security cameras
around his house turned up nothing.

385
00:26:06,870 --> 00:26:08,338
What about you, Ms. Kudo?

386
00:26:08,405 --> 00:26:11,374
Because of confidentiality,
the city office won't say anything.

387
00:26:11,441 --> 00:26:12,542
Why?

388
00:26:12,609 --> 00:26:13,910
The evidence is all there.

389
00:26:13,977 --> 00:26:15,612
Let's talk over here.

390
00:26:16,112 --> 00:26:18,214
That man killed my father.

391
00:26:18,848 --> 00:26:20,116
-Why?
-What's happened?

392
00:26:22,352 --> 00:26:23,253
This.

393
00:26:23,319 --> 00:26:25,488
I KILLED MY COWORKER 32 YEARS AGO
A CONFESSION 17 YEARS AFTER THE STATUTE

394
00:26:25,555 --> 00:26:27,657
An unsolved disappearance case.

395
00:26:28,258 --> 00:26:32,128
The culprit buried the body
under the boards in his garden,

396
00:26:32,195 --> 00:26:34,831
but it was being dug up
for land readjustment.

397
00:26:34,898 --> 00:26:36,933
Seems he turned himself in yesterday.

398
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:39,669
But the case's statute of limitations
expired in 2009.

399
00:26:39,736 --> 00:26:41,838
You know who the culprit is.

400
00:26:41,905 --> 00:26:44,507
Arrest him! Please!

401
00:26:44,574 --> 00:26:46,342
-Please.
-Ishizaka.

402
00:26:49,546 --> 00:26:50,447
Okay.

403
00:26:52,115 --> 00:26:55,919
If only the case had been one year later.

404
00:26:56,519 --> 00:26:59,189
No more statute of limitations
for murders after 2009…

405
00:26:59,255 --> 00:27:00,256
Hello.

406
00:27:02,058 --> 00:27:03,860
Don't tell Tagusari.

407
00:27:03,927 --> 00:27:04,961
Why?

408
00:27:06,129 --> 00:27:08,331
Come on, just go with him.

409
00:27:20,443 --> 00:27:23,713
First Division will re-examine
Uno’s background and relationships.

410
00:27:24,247 --> 00:27:28,017
Aoi Station investigators, expand the
search area from Ms. Nishiura’s home

411
00:27:28,084 --> 00:27:29,452
and check security cameras.

412
00:27:29,519 --> 00:27:30,520
Yes, sir!

413
00:27:34,124 --> 00:27:36,760
If we can confirm Uno’s face
on a security camera…

414
00:27:36,826 --> 00:27:38,394
I won't let him get away.

415
00:27:38,461 --> 00:27:40,063
I'll crush his alibi.

416
00:27:46,369 --> 00:27:47,604
Excuse me.

417
00:27:47,670 --> 00:27:49,706
I'm from the Aoi Station.

418
00:27:50,974 --> 00:27:53,643
Could we check your CCTV footage?

419
00:27:53,710 --> 00:27:55,278
It's right here.

420
00:27:55,345 --> 00:27:56,312
Thank you.

421
00:27:56,379 --> 00:27:58,882
-Please let me know when you're finished.
-We will.

422
00:28:00,950 --> 00:28:03,286
I'll fast-forward to May 13th.

423
00:28:10,393 --> 00:28:11,461
I'll be right back.

424
00:28:13,763 --> 00:28:15,064
Yes, this is Kudo.

425
00:28:20,970 --> 00:28:22,505
Are you working?

426
00:28:26,843 --> 00:28:27,911
Why are you here?

427
00:28:27,977 --> 00:28:30,346
I just had some business around here.

428
00:28:30,914 --> 00:28:31,915
Business?

429
00:28:31,981 --> 00:28:36,419
Didn't you use to live in Yomogida?

430
00:28:39,856 --> 00:28:40,890
How do you know that?

431
00:28:41,758 --> 00:28:42,926
So I was right.

432
00:28:42,992 --> 00:28:47,564
I thought I had heard the name
Tagusari somewhere before,

433
00:28:47,630 --> 00:28:49,566
so I searched for it online.

434
00:28:51,401 --> 00:28:52,769
I see.

435
00:28:53,803 --> 00:28:55,572
So you became a detective.

436
00:28:57,140 --> 00:28:59,008
Is it out of a sense of justice?

437
00:29:00,043 --> 00:29:03,780
Or is there some other reason?

438
00:29:08,818 --> 00:29:10,620
Don't worry about me.

439
00:29:18,261 --> 00:29:21,865
Mr. Uno lost his dear wife in an accident.

440
00:29:23,466 --> 00:29:28,738
But the driver, Ms. Nishiura,
insisted it was his wife’s fault

441
00:29:28,805 --> 00:29:31,541
and refused to admit
her own mistake until the very end.

442
00:29:33,376 --> 00:29:34,978
Even though she killed someone,

443
00:29:35,678 --> 00:29:38,581
she wasn't held accountable for the crime.

444
00:29:40,583 --> 00:29:44,020
After that, Ms. Nishiura,
supported by her boyfriend,

445
00:29:44,087 --> 00:29:47,690
began returning to society, and started

446
00:29:49,759 --> 00:29:51,227
driving a car again.

447
00:29:56,199 --> 00:29:58,134
Everything goes back to normal.

448
00:29:59,636 --> 00:30:02,071
Except for Mr. Uno’s wife, who was gone.

449
00:30:08,111 --> 00:30:10,346
You know the pain
of the forgotten bereaved,

450
00:30:11,714 --> 00:30:13,116
don't you?

451
00:30:25,128 --> 00:30:28,064
Why don't you stop carrying
the burden all by yourself?

452
00:30:29,399 --> 00:30:33,136
Please, tell me what's at your core.

453
00:30:35,171 --> 00:30:36,806
Today, at 6:00 p.m.

454
00:30:36,873 --> 00:30:38,975
I'll be waiting for you
at the city office.

455
00:30:47,884 --> 00:30:50,987
Hey, check your phone!

456
00:30:51,054 --> 00:30:52,522
Haruko called me.

457
00:30:52,588 --> 00:30:54,624
She said she couldn't get through to you.

458
00:30:55,458 --> 00:30:56,426
I see.

459
00:30:56,926 --> 00:30:59,529
You're investigating Ms. Hatano
from the city office?

460
00:31:01,130 --> 00:31:02,732
I was just a little curious.

461
00:31:03,933 --> 00:31:05,501
How was the CCTV footage?

462
00:31:10,873 --> 00:31:12,742
Nothing was caught on camera.

463
00:31:13,443 --> 00:31:14,744
I see.

464
00:31:15,912 --> 00:31:18,314
-Haruko is asking to meet.
-I'll leave it to you.

465
00:31:34,764 --> 00:31:35,999
Where's Makoto?

466
00:31:37,066 --> 00:31:39,369
It seems he has
some business to attend to.

467
00:31:41,537 --> 00:31:45,041
The other day, Mr. Tagusari and I
were talking about family.

468
00:31:45,608 --> 00:31:47,510
What about you, Haruko?

469
00:31:48,244 --> 00:31:49,579
What?

470
00:31:49,645 --> 00:31:51,180
Do you see your family?

471
00:31:55,084 --> 00:31:56,352
I do.

472
00:31:57,153 --> 00:31:58,821
I see my father here.

473
00:32:01,190 --> 00:32:03,359
It was so long ago,

474
00:32:04,660 --> 00:32:06,763
he got drunk and fell into the sea.

475
00:32:09,665 --> 00:32:12,702
My mom and brother died in an accident
when I was in grade school.

476
00:32:16,205 --> 00:32:19,742
I couldn't say goodbye or thank you.

477
00:32:23,012 --> 00:32:26,582
So, it might be better
to see your mother while you still can.

478
00:32:31,888 --> 00:32:32,755
Okay.

479
00:32:35,091 --> 00:32:37,794
From that reply,
I'm sure you won't see her.

480
00:32:41,264 --> 00:32:42,899
You're sharp, Haruko.

481
00:32:45,001 --> 00:32:46,502
Oh, right.

482
00:32:47,270 --> 00:32:48,838
Before I forget.

483
00:32:51,240 --> 00:32:52,942
Oh, it’s about Ms. Hatano, right?

484
00:32:53,009 --> 00:32:54,077
Right.

485
00:32:54,577 --> 00:32:58,514
No matter where I dug,
I only heard good rumors about her.

486
00:32:59,348 --> 00:33:00,516
I knew it.

487
00:33:01,117 --> 00:33:03,986
I wonder why Mr. Tagusari
made you look into her?

488
00:33:05,254 --> 00:33:08,224
Are the drugs being delivered today?

489
00:33:08,291 --> 00:33:12,228
Based on the college student's testimony,
we're going to raid the Igarashi-gumi now.

490
00:33:12,862 --> 00:33:15,998
I'm sure they have other offenses,
so go and do a thorough sweep.

491
00:33:16,065 --> 00:33:17,266
I know.

492
00:33:21,237 --> 00:33:23,272
I heard all about it.

493
00:33:23,339 --> 00:33:24,874
You caught onto something big!

494
00:33:24,941 --> 00:33:27,810
I handed it over
to the Organized Crime Department.

495
00:33:27,877 --> 00:33:30,346
What? What a waste.

496
00:33:30,413 --> 00:33:32,715
They said they'll pay back
the favor someday.

497
00:33:33,649 --> 00:33:37,753
Still, you did great
finding out the delivery date.

498
00:33:37,820 --> 00:33:39,355
It was just a coincidence.

499
00:33:40,456 --> 00:33:44,360
MAKOTO - WE'RE SWEEPING THE IGARASHI-GUMI
I'M SURE WE'LL FIND TSUDA'S NOTEBOOK

500
00:33:52,168 --> 00:33:55,438
<i>Today at 6:00 p.m. I'll be waiting</i>
<i>for you at the city office.</i>

501
00:34:04,647 --> 00:34:07,850
The users of the Welfare and Health
Department that Uno visited.

502
00:34:07,917 --> 00:34:10,353
You did well to get this.

503
00:34:10,419 --> 00:34:12,488
The city office's security must be tight.

504
00:34:12,555 --> 00:34:15,324
It's thanks to an informant
Mr. Tagusari uses.

505
00:34:15,391 --> 00:34:16,559
Tagusari?

506
00:34:16,626 --> 00:34:19,061
She's a former newspaper reporter,
very capable.

507
00:34:21,030 --> 00:34:21,864
Ms. Kudo.

508
00:34:22,365 --> 00:34:25,735
-Is anything wrong with the users here?
-Here.

509
00:34:25,801 --> 00:34:26,802
ATSUKO NARITA

510
00:34:26,869 --> 00:34:28,237
Atsuko Narita?

511
00:34:28,738 --> 00:34:30,840
The mother from the entrance exam case?

512
00:34:31,407 --> 00:34:35,378
Ms. Hatano, the consultant,
was in charge of both Uno and Narita.

513
00:34:35,444 --> 00:34:39,415
Doesn't it bother you that she's
consulting with two of our suspects?

514
00:34:39,482 --> 00:34:41,384
Sayoko Hatano…

515
00:34:41,450 --> 00:34:45,655
However, she has a good reputation
among other staff and users.

516
00:34:45,721 --> 00:34:48,724
Uno purchased an old vehicle
that was about to be scrapped.

517
00:34:48,791 --> 00:34:49,959
About to be scrapped?

518
00:34:50,026 --> 00:34:51,160
Why would he buy it?

519
00:34:51,227 --> 00:34:54,730
Around the same time, he also got
an exhaust gas meter from the shop.

520
00:34:54,797 --> 00:34:56,799
Was he experimenting with exhaust leaks?

521
00:34:56,866 --> 00:34:58,267
Bring him in for voluntary questioning.

522
00:34:58,334 --> 00:34:59,535
Yes, sir!

523
00:35:20,723 --> 00:35:23,259
MINORU

524
00:35:30,032 --> 00:35:32,168
I knew you would come.

525
00:35:33,603 --> 00:35:34,837
Makoto Tagusari.

526
00:35:39,775 --> 00:35:42,311
-I'm here to ask about Uno--
-No need for pretenses.

527
00:35:44,880 --> 00:35:48,417
"Logic doesn't solve anything."

528
00:35:49,352 --> 00:35:50,319
Right?

529
00:35:56,158 --> 00:35:58,661
The year was 1995.

530
00:35:59,362 --> 00:36:01,664
April 26th.

531
00:36:03,899 --> 00:36:05,901
The burden was far too heavy

532
00:36:06,669 --> 00:36:09,572
for a seven-year-old boy to carry.

533
00:36:13,242 --> 00:36:16,345
You've walked a long way to get here.

534
00:36:19,782 --> 00:36:24,487
Could you tell me about that journey?

535
00:36:27,857 --> 00:36:31,294
Here, you don't have to hide anything.

536
00:36:35,298 --> 00:36:36,565
What happened after?

537
00:36:42,171 --> 00:36:43,639
After the incident,

538
00:36:45,441 --> 00:36:47,977
I went to live at a relative's house.

539
00:36:50,479 --> 00:36:51,580
There,

540
00:36:53,582 --> 00:36:56,352
I just waited and waited
for the culprit to be caught.

541
00:36:59,689 --> 00:37:01,691
"He'll be caught soon."

542
00:37:03,693 --> 00:37:05,928
Everyone was saying nice things like that.

543
00:37:07,163 --> 00:37:07,997
But…

544
00:37:08,831 --> 00:37:12,768
as a child, you had no choice
but to believe them.

545
00:37:16,272 --> 00:37:17,540
I hoped,

546
00:37:19,508 --> 00:37:21,010
and I was let down.

547
00:37:23,713 --> 00:37:26,182
My younger brother became
more and more withdrawn.

548
00:37:30,052 --> 00:37:32,755
The police, who used to come every day,

549
00:37:34,156 --> 00:37:36,058
started coming once a week,

550
00:37:37,159 --> 00:37:38,861
then once a month.

551
00:37:40,429 --> 00:37:42,031
"We're still investigating."

552
00:37:44,533 --> 00:37:47,703
No matter how often I asked,
they only gave me the same lines.

553
00:37:52,541 --> 00:37:53,709
And then…

554
00:37:54,443 --> 00:37:56,479
the world went back to its daily routine.

555
00:38:00,916 --> 00:38:04,420
Everyone began to forget
about the incident.

556
00:38:12,228 --> 00:38:13,496
Everyone…

557
00:38:15,531 --> 00:38:18,167
began to forget about the incident.

558
00:38:19,502 --> 00:38:20,436
Right.

559
00:38:21,670 --> 00:38:22,705
Everyone.

560
00:38:26,876 --> 00:38:28,244
Everyone…

561
00:38:32,982 --> 00:38:34,216
started to forget…

562
00:38:37,586 --> 00:38:38,721
about my mom…

563
00:38:40,389 --> 00:38:41,524
and dad.

564
00:38:42,658 --> 00:38:46,595
As if nothing ever happened.

565
00:38:51,700 --> 00:38:52,902
I was…

566
00:38:55,404 --> 00:38:56,572
scared of that.

567
00:39:01,477 --> 00:39:02,645
And then…

568
00:39:03,279 --> 00:39:06,849
on April 26, 2010…

569
00:39:09,285 --> 00:39:12,521
the case reached
its statute of limitations.

570
00:39:15,558 --> 00:39:17,493
It's only a two-day difference.

571
00:39:19,795 --> 00:39:21,497
Sometimes I think about it.

572
00:39:23,265 --> 00:39:24,366
What if…

573
00:39:26,936 --> 00:39:30,139
the culprit had come just two days later?

574
00:39:32,308 --> 00:39:33,642
What if…

575
00:39:35,411 --> 00:39:38,581
the statute of limitations had been
abolished two days earlier?

576
00:39:41,217 --> 00:39:42,785
We could have arrested him.

577
00:39:46,188 --> 00:39:48,290
What difference do two days make?

578
00:39:49,492 --> 00:39:50,826
People were killed,

579
00:39:52,528 --> 00:39:54,363
just the same.

580
00:39:57,533 --> 00:40:01,103
The culprit doesn't just hurt you once.

581
00:40:02,738 --> 00:40:07,543
They continue to make you suffer
over and over, forever.

582
00:40:13,082 --> 00:40:16,218
Without the incident, by now,
what would you be doing?

583
00:40:20,456 --> 00:40:21,624
Gotten married?

584
00:40:24,727 --> 00:40:28,230
Or would you have gone abroad?

585
00:40:38,941 --> 00:40:40,276
To be honest…

586
00:40:41,277 --> 00:40:42,244
Yes?

587
00:40:46,148 --> 00:40:47,883
To be honest…

588
00:40:52,655 --> 00:40:54,990
I wanted a job where I could make things.

589
00:40:57,059 --> 00:40:58,427
Like my dad.

590
00:41:04,066 --> 00:41:08,737
You have been trapped in that day forever.

591
00:41:12,274 --> 00:41:15,010
How do you think it can be resolved?

592
00:41:18,547 --> 00:41:19,381
That's…

593
00:41:20,082 --> 00:41:21,617
I told you, didn't I?

594
00:41:23,285 --> 00:41:25,187
We don't need logic here.

595
00:41:29,725 --> 00:41:33,696
Even if the culprit is caught,
what changes?

596
00:41:36,599 --> 00:41:37,900
The investigation ends,

597
00:41:38,500 --> 00:41:40,002
the trial ends,

598
00:41:40,903 --> 00:41:44,573
and eventually, the culprit's punishment
comes to an end too.

599
00:41:48,911 --> 00:41:49,845
But…

600
00:41:50,946 --> 00:41:54,383
the pain of the bereaved never changes.

601
00:41:57,720 --> 00:42:00,255
Only the bereaved
who have lost their loved ones…

602
00:42:01,090 --> 00:42:02,157
Why?

603
00:42:03,559 --> 00:42:06,128
Why must they be the ones
to continue suffering?

604
00:42:11,900 --> 00:42:13,102
Makoto!

605
00:42:13,168 --> 00:42:14,803
Wait for me!

606
00:42:19,375 --> 00:42:20,409
Dad!

607
00:42:20,476 --> 00:42:21,910
Mom!

608
00:42:22,478 --> 00:42:25,080
I'll definitely find the killer!

609
00:42:38,460 --> 00:42:42,197
THINGS HAVE TURNED FOR THE WORSE

610
00:42:50,305 --> 00:42:51,440
Uno left this behind!

611
00:42:52,041 --> 00:42:54,243
Search Uno's house and its surroundings!

612
00:42:54,810 --> 00:42:56,378
The pain the victim felt,

613
00:42:57,780 --> 00:42:59,682
and the pain the perpetrator feels…

614
00:43:00,849 --> 00:43:02,017
Now, they're equal.

615
00:43:05,854 --> 00:43:07,156
They're even.

616
00:43:10,659 --> 00:43:12,394
If the culprit hasn't been caught,

617
00:43:13,829 --> 00:43:16,031
the bereaved shouldn't be arrested either.

618
00:43:18,267 --> 00:43:19,535
Nice and even.

619
00:43:22,171 --> 00:43:23,472
Nice and even.

620
00:43:28,577 --> 00:43:29,845
Nice and even.

621
00:43:48,997 --> 00:43:52,034
<i>-However you look at it, it’s suicide.</i>
-This isn't suicide, it’s murder.

622
00:43:52,101 --> 00:43:53,936
<i>She might have been inciting the murders.</i>

623
00:43:54,002 --> 00:43:56,071
Tell me what's at your core.

624
00:43:56,138 --> 00:43:57,940
Sayoko Hatano is the enemy.

625
00:43:58,006 --> 00:43:58,941
<i>I'm sorry.</i>

626
00:43:59,007 --> 00:44:00,275
Subtitle translation by: Nix S.

